&#xa0;
[normal]Memorandum from Sikorsky Aircraft Corporation (HCS0014)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Sikorsky Aircraft Corporation thanks the Transport Committee for the opportunity to testify on the evidence of safety of Sikorsky helicopter flights to offshore installations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This 
[normal]memo:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](a) Introduces Sikorsky Aircraft
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](b) Responds to the Transport Committee’s questions regarding the safety of helicopter flights to offshore installations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Sikorsky Aircraft Corporation is a recognized world leader in 
[normal]helicopter design, manufacture and support. The company’s commercial products include the S-76™ and S- 92® aircraft. Both aircraft are capable of delivering off-shore oil support and are certified to the highest safety standards. The S-92® aircraft is the 
[normal]first and only helicopter in its class certified to the latest U.S. Federal Aviation Administration and European airworthiness safety standards.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Today, Sikorsky Aircraft Corp. stays true to the legacy of Igor Sikorsky with a mission statement that encom
[normal]passes his passion for safety and innovation: "We pioneer flight solutions that bring people home everywhere...every time."™ Sikorsky helicopters have saved an estimated two million lives since performing the world's first helicopter rescue in 1944.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Sik
[normal]orsky is a subsidiary of United Technologies Corporation (UTC), which is the 39th largest manufacturer in the U.S. and the 59th largest publicly held manufacturer in the world. United Technologies (UTC) is a diversified company that provides a broad range 
[normal]of high-technology products and services to the global aerospace and building systems industries. Our commercial businesses are Otis elevators and escalators and UTC Climate, Controls &amp; Security, a leading provider of heating, ventilation, air conditioning
[normal], fire and security systems, building automation and controls. Our aerospace businesses are Sikorsky aircraft and the new UTC Propulsion &amp; Aerospace Systems, which includes Pratt &amp; Whitney aircraft engines and UTC Aerospace Systems aerospace products. The 
[normal]company also operates a central research organization that pursues technologies for
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]improving
[normal] the performance, energy efficiency and cost of UTC products and processes. UTC recently was named as Fortune Magazine’s “Most Admired Aerospace and 
[normal]Defense
[normal] Comp
[normal]any.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Sikorsky was founded in 1923 as the Aero Engineering Corporation by aerospace pioneer and legend Igor Sikorsky. The company was acquired in 1929 by the United Aircraft and Transportation Corporation, which later became United Technologies Corporat
[normal]ion.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]At Sikorsky Aircraft Corp., we share in the culture of safety, and we are committed to the success of helicopter flights to offshore installations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Statistics:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The S-92® helicopter has the best-in-class accident rate in the 
[normal]medium-lift helicopter market at 0.32 accidents per 100,000 flight hours versus a comparable aircraft model at 1.74. The S-92® aircraft is comparable to the fixed wing Part 121 scheduled airline at 0.15 accidents per 100,000 flight hours.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There have been 
[normal]two accidents in the S-92® helicopter’s history, one in South Korea in 2008 and one off the Newfoundland coast in 2009. The comparison of fatal accident rates has the S-92® helicopter at 0.16 per 100,000 flight hours, with the comparable aircraft model at 
[normal]0.67 per 100,000 flight hours.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The S-76™ aircraft also has a world-class accident rate in its market segment, at 1.42 per 100,000 flight hours, as compared to its competition at 1.58 per 100,000 flight hours. The comparison of fatal accident rates shows t
[normal]he S-76 at 0.50 per 100,000 flight hours, with the competition at 0.92 per 100,000 flight hours.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]S-92® Aircraft:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The S-92® aircraft is the first and only helicopter in its class certified to the latest U.S. Federal Aviation Administration Part 29 require
[normal]ments and European airworthiness safety standards incorporating the latest specifications for flaw tolerance, bird strike capability and turbine burst protection. The S-92® helicopter’s design has the highest crashworthy standards and also exceeds the egre
[normal]ss requirements.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There are 189 S-92® aircraft in operation in 24 countries around the world. The 200th completed aircraft was delivered in September 2013, and the fleet has flown more than 625,000 hours, 90 percent of which are logged in the off-shore oil
[normal] transportation. Offshore oil S-92® helicopters fly an estimated 90-110 hours per month; the high time aircraft has surpassed 15,000 flight hours to date. There are now four aircraft with more than 13,000 flight hours.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Some of the key safety features of 
[normal]the S-92® helicopter include energy-absorbing landing gear, high visibility crew station, traffic collision avoidance system, APU in-flight emergency power, redundant hydraulics and flaw tolerant flight controls, reduced workload EFIS cockpit, high energy 
[normal]turbine burst protection, large cabin emergency exits, RIG Approach, emergency beacon, 20g crash retention, enhanced ground proximity warning system, HEELS, Sea State Six, push-out window exits for each row, crash- worthy fuel system separated from cabin (
[normal]passengers), energy-absorbing passenger and crew seats, bird strike certification, lightning strike protection and emergency life rafts.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The S-92® helicopter’s lube system fully isolates external leaks, maintains cooling in the event of a pump failure and
[normal] has redundant pump drives. Both the external leak and pump failure modes were tested in excess of three hours.
[normal]&#xa0;
